<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-513-046  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 513 046.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 p51(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multimegabit switched service on trial. (broadband ISDN)(includesrelated article on IEEE Standard 802.6 specification formetropolitan area networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local-exchange telephone companies are moving toward broadbandISDN technology, while will allow the delivery of integratedvoice, data and video information over public fiber-opticnetworks.andP;  Switched multimegabit data service (SMDS), a precursorto broadband ISDN, will deliver imaging and multimediaapplications over public networks at speeds of up to 45M-bps.andO;SMDS is a high-level protocol that uses the developing IEEE 802.6standard to let users extend local networks over entire cities andwill match the high-level application layers of LANs.andP;  Someobservers warn that SMDS may not offer an easy migration path tobroadband ISDN because the two technologies have incompatibleframing approaches.andP;  True broadband ISDN will not appear untilaround 1994, but tariffed SMDS will be available by 1991.andP;  Bell ofPennsylvania and Pacific Bell have already announces SMDS trials.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone companiesISDNBroadbandCommunications Service SuppliersBandwidth.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>